sec.p:
In the sequel, we use the following notation:


the unit tensor 1 such as 1v=v∀v.;

the skew-symmetric tensor u∧ (u∧T=-u∧) such as the vector product can be written as u×v=u∧v∀v.

In order to extend this comparative study, the driving forces are computed from the different IDM using different sets of geometric and dynamic parameters. The horizontal trajectory near leg’s passive singularities introduced in section ‘Horizontal motion of point P near leg passive singularities’ is also used (cf. Table 2 and Figure 10). The height of the platform is Z coordinate of the horizontal trajectory. The geometric configuration (cf. Figure 15) of the manipulators is described by the radius of the platform (Rp), the radius of the base (Rb) and the distribution of the joints’ angles on the platform (βP) and the base (βB). Knowing that the inertia matrices are proportional to mass, the dynamic parameters used for the comparative study are the total masses of the legs: mleg = 6*(m2 + m3) and the platform mass: mP. The variation of the following set of dimensionless parameters is applied on the different models to compare the driving force computations for various manipulator configurations:


the ratio of the radius of the platform to the radius of the base (RP/RB);

the ratio of the height of the platform to the radius of the base (Z/Rb);

the distribution of the joints’ angles on the platform and the base;

the ratio between of the legs to the platform masses (mleg/mP).

